    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter">
                <head type="title">Camillo Ghilino to Miklós Oláh ([Rome?], 2 April 1535) </head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p>They are happy to hear that the Queen is better, Ambrogio Candiano is an
                            excellent specialist. German infantrymen are boarding ships at
                            Portofino, in four days Andrea Doria will take them to Hispania at the
                            Emperor’s order. There is nothing to fear regarding Hayreddin Barbarossa
                            Pasha either, he will get his just punishment. Oláh also already knows
                            that the Sultan has been beaten by the Persians, he has lost all his
                            military equipment, and his money is also gone, so the Emperor may soon
                            become the ruler of the entire world. The Pope tends to side with the
                            French, but he does not dare show it openly; the Veneti are loyal to the
                            Emperor. The Prince of Ferrara laughs at the Italian alliance; and a
                            feud has erupted among the Helvetians. </p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p>Idem Nicolao Olao suo salutem. </p>
                <p>Unas tuas litteras VII. Martii datas<note type="critic">We do not know
                        this letter.</note> proxime accepi, quibus me mones de omni statu rerum
                    nostrarum, quod mirum in modum et <persName>principi</persName><note
                        type="critic">Francesco II Sforza.</note> meo et mihi gratum fuit.
                        <persName>Reginae</persName><note type="critic">Queen Mary of
                        Hungary.</note> valetudinem indies fieri meliorem laetamur, utinam per
                    aliquot saltem dies <choice>
                        <orig>medicis</orig>
                        <supplied>medici</supplied>
                    </choice> dicto audiens esset, non enim vererer, quod pristinas vires brevi
                    recuperatura esset. In <persName>Candiano</persName><note type="critic">Ambrogio
                        Candiano.</note> fidem aut diligentiam non desiderabitis, vir certe probus
                    est, et in re medica experientissimus. Germani pedites inter portum
                        Delphini<note type="critic">Portofino. “Pliny; a port on the coast of
                        Liguria. Now Porto Fino, and fifteen miles to the east, of Genoa”, see <hi
                            rend="smallcap">MacBean</hi> 1773.</note> et Lunae<note type="critic"
                        >Lunae portus: “Strabo; a very extensive port, or more truly a bay of
                        Liguria, between Portus Veneris and Portus Ericis, twenty miles compass”,
                        see <hi rend="smallcap">MacBean</hi> 1773.</note> conscendere, quatriduo
                    post <persName>Andreas Auria</persName> cum XV triremibus suis transmittet in
                    Hispaniam caesaris iussu. Is nunc primum <placeName>Barchinonae</placeName><note
                        type="critic">Barcelona.</note> agit, classis eius cum
                        <placeName>Luctatii</placeName><note type="critic">Probably Lucca, but it is
                        not clear.</note> classe omnino conferenda est et numero navium et militum
                    et remigum experientia, cuius adventus in Aphricam summe a <persName>Tuneti
                        regulo</persName><note type="critic">Abu Abdallah Muhammad V al-Hasa.</note>
                    et illius clitellis exspectatur. Quare fac, bono animo sis. Nec
                        <persName>Aenobarbi</persName><note type="critic">Hayreddin Barbarossa
                        Pasha.</note> vires pertimescendae sunt, dabit enim poenas sceleratissimus
                    reipublicae Christianae hostis illatorum nobis damnorum. Eum pro certo habemus
                    et a pecunia et militibus flagitiose imparatum esse, et si
                        <persName>Gallo</persName> suasere classem nostram opperietur, quos risus
                    brevi edet? Credo te iam intellexisse caesaris Turcarum copias a Persa
                    labefactatas fuisse, bellicis tormentis omnibus amissis, et pecunia intercepta,
                    quae tunc ei expeditissima erat, haec cum nobis quotidie per certissimos homines
                    confirmantur, nos monent veriora esse veris, et Deum nostrum caesarem omnino
                    totius orbis imperio brevi potiturum. <persName>Pontifex</persName><note
                        type="critic">Pope Paul III.</note> edentulus in Gallionis partes propensior
                    est, sed tamen hiscere non audebit, Veneta respublica non deseret caesarem.
                        <persName>Dux Ferrariae</persName><note type="critic">Ercole II d’Este
                        (1508–1559) was Duke of Ferrara from 1534.</note> foedus Italicum irrisit,
                    quando cum reliquis Italiae proceribus consentire noluit, spero deos illi fore
                    iratos. Helvetii nuper inter se dissidere coeperunt. Credo ob
                        <placeName>Genevae</placeName> defectionem<note type="critic">I.e.
                        Calvinism.</note> a <persName>duce Allobrogensi</persName><note
                        type="critic">Charles III of Savoy (1486–1553), Duke of Savoy. The
                        Allobroges were a Gallic people living below the river Rhine and the Alps
                        during the Roman period.</note> utrinque tamen ab armis abstinetur.
                        <persName>Sceperum</persName><note type="critic">Cornelis de
                        Schepper.</note> nostrum meo nomine salutabis, item reliquos omnes amicos
                    meos et praesertim lectissimam <persName>Virginem Lucretiam
                        Caballam</persName>,<note type="critic">Lucretia Caballis (vom Ross).</note>
                    et Gilini tui memor semper esto. Vale. </p>
                <p>Ex vico Iovis<note type="critic">Vicus Iovis Fagutalis was a street on
                        the Esquiline Hill in Rome.</note> VI. Nonas Aprilis MDXXXV.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
